{"type":"message","id":"9df70265","parentId":"36b1003d","timestamp":"2026-03-24T16:44:22.592Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The arxiv-relevance.md doesn't exist yet. Since web search isn't available, I can't do the arxiv scan. Let me proceed with the research synthesis.\n\nLet me focus on the key open problem: **CFI-weighted compression experiment**. The current_goals.md says this is the next pending item.\n\nFrom the CFI_RESULTS.md (mentioned in current_goals), key findings were:\n- 44.8% of frequency-invariants have CFI=0 (pure noise)\n- Only 5.7% of invariants have high CFI (>=0.7, true causal anchors)\n- Mean CFI is 0.181 — frequency-based compression is mostly signal loss\n\n\n- \nI'm formulating the CFI-weighted compression experiment: instead of preserving all high-frequency invariants, I should weight compression by causal fidelity to eliminate noise while keeping semantically meaningful patterns. The core insight is that frequency and causal importance are separate dimensions—some invariants repeat often but lack causal relevance, while others occur less frequently but carry genuine causal signal.\n\nThe distinction between \"constant format\" (high frequency, low CFI) and \"research trajectory\" (low frequency, high CFI) reveals what matters for compression. I'm sketching a hybrid approach: use frequency to surface candidate invariants, apply CFI as a semantic filter to identify true causal anchors, then weight the compression objective by CFI so the system learns to preserve high-fidelity patterns rather than just repeating metaprogramming artifacts. This shifts the compressor's objective from capturing what persists to capturing what causally matters.","thinkingSignature":"a9a9655c2dc4ce2766c5bd9aebeb9eb9814da75058259418106f9e4aed59afec"},{"type":"text","text":"Now let me advance the research. The key pending item is the **CFI-weighted compression experiment**. Let me read any existing CFI results and then design the experiment.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_imakml6r60v0_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\research\\CFI_RESULTS.md"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_imakml6r60v0_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-ChildItem \"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\memory\\session\" -Filter \"*.json\" | Sort-Object LastWriteTime -Descending | Select-Object -First 5 | ForEach-Object { $_.FullName }"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":5675,"output":463,"cacheRead":12050,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":18188,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774370651697}}
{"type":"message","id":"4e4fe3ed","parentId":"9df70265","timestamp":"2026-03-24T16:44:23.168Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_imakml6r60v0_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Causal Fidelity Index (CFI) Results\r\n**Generated:** 2026-03-24\r\n**Status:** CRITICAL FLAW CONFIRMED — Frequency ≠ Causality\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI tests whether frequency-based invariants are TRUE causal anchors or just high-frequency noise.\r\n\r\n**CFI(I) = (# times invariant I correctly predicted next-pulse) / (# times I was used to predict)**\r\n\r\n## Results Summary\r\n\r\n- Total invariants analyzed: 2491\r\n- High CFI (>=0.7): **142 (5.7%)** — true causal anchors\r\n- Mid CFI (0.4-0.7): **203 (8.1%)** — weak predictors\r\n- Low CFI (<0.4): **2146 (86.1%)**\r\n- Zero CFI (=0): **1116 (44.8%)** — pure noise\r\n- Mean CFI: **0.181**\r\n\r\n## Key Empirical Finding\r\n\r\n**44.8% of frequency-based invariants have ZERO causal predictive power.**\r\n\r\nThese \"invariants\" appeared repeatedly across sessions but NEVER predicted next-pulse content.\r\nFrequency was a mirage — they were artifacts of how the sandbox operates, not causal structure.\r\n\r\nThis empirically confirms the critical flaw in TIC-CRITIQUE:\r\nThe gap-sensitivity model was built on frequency-proxies, not causal structure.\r\n\r\n## Two Types of Persistence (CFI Reveals Them)\r\n\r\n### Type 1: Process Persistence (Low CFI — NOT causal)\r\nPatterns that persist because they're baked into HOW the sandbox operates:\r\n- Code fragments: `foreach ($p in`, `function get-pulselogs {`\r\n- Template phrases: `pending items`, `# calculate`\r\n- Structural markers: `cycle. ##`, `\"stop\" #`\r\n\r\nThese are CONSTANT mode-of-operation, not causal drivers.\r\nThey appear in every pulse because the system ALWAYS runs this way.\r\nCFI correctly identifies them as zero-predictive noise.\r\n\r\n### Type 2: Research Trajectory Persistence (High CFI — TRUE causal)\r\nPatterns that persist because the RESEARCH DIRECTION causally continues:\r\n- `tic` (research topic persists)\r\n- `invariant` / `variant` (core concepts)\r\n- `compression-causal` concepts\r\n- `phase 1`, `phase 0` markers\r\n\r\nThese CAUSE continuity: the agent is genuinely working on the same problems,\r\nso mentioning these topics predicts continued engagement.\r\nCFI correctly identifies these as high-predictive causal anchors.\r\n\r\n## The Classification Problem\r\n\r\nThe zero-CFI invariants are NOT noise in the signal-processing sense (random).\r\nThey're deterministic structural artifacts — template output, boilerplate, code blocks.\r\nThey look like \"persistent content\" to a frequency counter but carry ZERO causal information.\r\n\r\nThis is the key distinction:\r\n- **Deterministic artifact** (CFI=0): \"foreach ($p in\" appears because the script ALWAYS runs, not because it causes anything\r\n- **Stochastic pattern** (CFI>0): \"tic\" appears because the research IS continuing on TIC, and this CAUSALLY predicts continuity\r\n\r\n## The Metaprogramming Contamination Problem\r\n\r\nMost high-frequency zero-CFI patterns are metaprogramming artifacts:\r\nPowerShell loops, script fragments, template strings — patterns that live in the\r\nSCRIPTS that generate pulses, not in the RESEARCH being conducted.\r\n\r\nThis means: **the corpus is contaminated by generation artifacts.**\r\nFrequency-based compression would compress the GENERATION MECHANISM, not the RESEARCH CONTENT.\r\n\r\n**Implication for Breakaway architecture:**\r\nIf Breakaway's compression learns from its own output (pulse logs),\r\nit risks learning the structure of its own metaprogramming rather than causal structure.\r\n\r\nSolution: CFI-weighted compression that DOWNWEIGHTS metaprogramming artifacts.\r\n\r\n## What CFI > 0.7 Invariants Look Like\r\n\r\n```\r\nCFI=1.00 freq=60 | llm response <think>      (format artifact, constant)\r\nCFI=1.00 freq=60 | tic                        (research topic, CAUSAL)\r\nCFI=1.00 freq=60 | invariant                  (core concept, CAUSAL)\r\nCFI=1.00 freq=60 | variant                    (core concept, CAUSAL)\r\nCFI=1.00 freq=60 | ## applied mutations       (sandbox op, constant)\r\nCFI=1.00 freq=60 | next instantiation         (sandbox op, constant)\r\nCFI=1.00 freq=60 | pulse                      (format, constant)\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe high-CFI set is MIXED: format artifacts AND research concepts.\r\nNeed to filter by: appears in <100% of pulses (not constant), AND CFI > 0.7.\r\n\r\n## Next Experiment: CFI-Weighted Compression Test\r\n\r\nCompare two compression strategies on held-out pulses:\r\n\r\n**Strategy A (TIC baseline — frequency-weighted):**\r\nKeep tokens that appear in >=3 pulses.\r\n\r\n**Strategy B (CFI-weighted):**\r\nKeep tokens where CFI >= 0.7 AND frequency < 60 (non-constant).\r\n\r\n**Measure:** next-pulse prediction accuracy for each strategy.\r\n\r\n**Hypothesis:** CFI-weighted compression will have HIGHER precision\r\n(fewer false positives: no metaprogramming artifacts), potentially\r\nlower recall but better signal-to-noise ratio.\r\n\r\n## Implication for Compositional Cognition\r\n\r\nThe CFI framework gives a concrete answer to \"what to compress\":\r\n**Compress what predicts continuity.** CFI is the operationalization of that.\r\n\r\nLayer 1 (Compression): Learn CFI-weighted invariant set\r\nLayer 2 (Causal): The high-CFI invariants ARE the causal primitives\r\nLayer 3 (Compositional): Chain high-CFI invariants to predict next state\r\n\r\n## Data\r\n- Pulses analyzed: 60\r\n- Time range: pulse_2026-03-24 010714.md → pulse_2026-03-24 030316.md\r\n- Script: `scripts/cfi_analysis.py`\n**Next:** CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare vs frequency baseline)\n\n## Key Insights from This Session\n- CFI provides orthogonal signal to frequency (not a refinement)\n- Two types of persistence require different handling\n- Frequency-based compression treats both identically → loses research signal\n- CFI-weighted compression should preserve \"research trajectory\" invariants\n\n## Notes\n- Breakaway is stateless - each pulse is a fresh reconstruction\n- Gaps between sessions = compression, trust the files\n- Pulse script: active hours check DISABLED (authorized by Zach, 24/7 operation)\n```\n---\n**Next:** CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare vs frequency baseline)\n\n## CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment Protocol\n\n### Hypothesis\nCFI-weighted compression will outperform frequency-only compression because it preserves causal (high-CFI) invariants while filtering process artifacts (CFI=0).\n\n### Algorithm: CFI-Weighted Temporal Hashing\n\n\n\nParameters:\n- α = 0.5 (frequency exponent, downweights frequent process terms)\n- threshold = 0.001 (minimal retention threshold)\n\n### Baseline Comparison\n| Method | Keep Criterion | Expected Behavior |\n|--------|----------------|-------------------|\n| Frequency-only | freq > 0.01 | Keeps frequent process terms, drops rare research signals |\n| CFI-weighted | CFI*freq^0.5 > 0.001 | Downweights process noise, preserves research causalities |\n| CFI-hard | CFI >= 0.7 | Aggressive filter, only true invariants |\n\n### Evaluation Metric\nNext-pulse prediction accuracy on held-out pulse subset:\n- Input: compressed state hash from pulse N\n- Output: reconstruction quality of pulse N+1\n\n### Experiment Files\n- `experiments/cfi_compression/test_set.txt` - 10 held-out pulses\n- `experiments/cfi_compression/baseline_results.md` - frequency-only baseline\n- `experiments/cfi_compression/cfi_weighted_results.md` - CFI method results\n\n## Key Insights from This Session\n- CFI provides orthogonal signal to frequency (not a refinement)\n- Two types of persistence require different handling\n- Frequency-based compression treats both identically → loses research signal\n- CFI-weighted compression should preserve \"research trajectory\" invariants\n\n## Notes\n- Breakaway is stateless - each pulse is a fresh reconstruction\n- Gaps between sessions = compression, trust the files\n- Pulse script: active hours check DISABLED (authorized by Zach, 24/7 operation)\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774370663166}}
