ring vs binary thresholds\n 33 \n 34 ## Pending\n-35 - [ ] CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\n+39 - [ ] Hybrid CFI×Freq scoring experiment (Strategy C)\n+40 - [ ] Distinguish \"constant format\" (freq≈160, CFI=1) from \"research trajectory\" (freq<120, CFI>0.5)\n 36 - [ ] Implement CFI filtering to remove metaprogramming contamination\n-37 - [ ] Distinguish \"constant format\" (freq=60, CFI=1) from \"research trajectory\" (freq<60, CFI>0.7)\n 38 - [ ] Wire Breakaway pulses to real TemporalAttention backend\n 39 - [ ] Design actual compression network (currently only analyzed text invariants)\n 40 \n 41 ## Key Insights from This Session\n 42 \n+47 1. **CFI and frequency are ORTHOGONAL signals** — combine both, don't choose one\n+48 2. **Constant-format tokens** (freq=160, CFI=1) are the trap — they look causal but aren't\n+49 3. **Three-dimensional compression filter**: CFI ≥ 0.5 AND freq ≥ 3 AND freq < 120\n+50 4. **Compression objective for Layer 1 is now concrete**: score(T) = CFI(T) × min(1, freq(T)/120)\n+51 \n+52 ## Key Insights from This Session\n+53 \n 43 1. **The gap IS the compression** — session boundaries are temporal hashing\n 44 2. **λ encodes both** — decay rate and gap threshold are the same parameter\n 45 3. **Three architectures, one synthesis** — Infant (catastrophic forgetting), TemporalAttention (focus decay), Breakaway (discontinuity) are complementary, not competing\n 46 4. **Breakaway's unique bet holds** — session gaps as compression is novel and correct\n    ...","firstChangedLine":26},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774370860465}}
